Step 7 - Examine correlation matrix, select variables based criteria:

  • Remove any variables that demonstrate a negligible relationship with vocabulary score (|r| < .100)
  • For each conceptual category, check for multicollinearity (|r| > .700).
  • For any collinear pairs, choose index with strongest theoretical rationale OR strongest correlation with vocabulary score

Step 8 - Create refined dataset, recheck collinearity

Remove variables identified in Step 7 and double check collinearity across conceptual categories - create refined dataset

Step 9 - Recheck multicollinearity

Model optimization approach - choose variable with strongest correlation (with vocabulary score) - remove any collinear variables (|r| > .700) - repeat with variable with next strongest correlation (etc.)

Conceptual approach - choose most theoretically/conceptually important variable - remove any collinear variables (|r| > .700) - repeat with second most theoretically/conceptually important variable (etc.)

Option 2 - Training/Test sets

(better argument for generalizability, but random selection can be unpredictable)

First, we need to organize our data:

set.seed(123) # for reproducible results (seed is for random number generator)
sample.size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(written_data_refined2)) #get number of rows for 75% of data
train.index <- sample(seq_len(nrow(written_data_refined2)), size = sample.size) #get random list of rows (75% of the data)
train <- written_data_refined2[train.index, ] #training set
test <- written_data_refined2[- train.index, ] #test set

Then, we create a model using the training set:

#create model with train set
model2 <- lm(vocabulary ~ mattr50_aw + COCA_lemma_magazine_bi_MI + Brysbaert_Concreteness_Combined_CW + Kuperman_AoA_CW + USF_CW_CW + McD_CD_CW, data = train)

Option 3: Cross-validation (Ten-fold)

Randomly splits the data into ten sections, then iteratively uses 90% to train a model that is then tested on the remaining 10% of the data. This is repeated until all sections of the dataset have been used as the test set.

#install.packages("caret")
library(caret)
ctrl.tenfold <- trainControl(method="cv", number=10) #create method

model3 <- train(vocabulary ~ mattr50_aw + COCA_lemma_magazine_bi_MI + Brysbaert_Concreteness_Combined_CW + Kuperman_AoA_CW + USF_CW_CW + McD_CD_CW, data = written_data_refined2, method = "lm", trControl = ctrl.tenfold)

Option 4: Cross-validation (LOOCV)

This is the same as Option 3, except that the model is trained on ALL of the data (except one row) and then tested on the remaining row. This is repeated until all data points have been used as the test data.

ctrl.loocv <- trainControl(method = "LOOCV") #create method

model4 <- train(vocabulary ~ mattr50_aw + COCA_lemma_magazine_bi_MI + Brysbaert_Concreteness_Combined_CW + Kuperman_AoA_CW + USF_CW_CW + McD_CD_CW, data = written_data_refined2, method = "lm", trControl = ctrl.loocv)
